  "missingCharacters": [
    {"name":"Balaam's Donkey","book":"Numbers","description":"The only animal in scripture to hold a conversation with its owner. Saw the angel of the LORD blocking the road when Balaam could not, and was given the power of speech to protest the beatings. A surprisingly eloquent equine theologian.","volumes":["OT"]},
    {"name":"Phinehas","book":"Numbers","description":"Son of Eleazar and grandson of Aaron. His zealous act at Baal-peor, executing an Israelite man and Midianite woman during the plague, turned away God's wrath and earned his family a covenant of an everlasting priesthood.","volumes":["OT"]},
    {"name":"Hobab","book":"Numbers","description":"Moses' brother-in-law (or father-in-law), a Midianite whom Moses asked to guide Israel through the wilderness because of his knowledge of the desert terrain.","volumes":["OT"]},
    {"name":"Zelophehad","book":"Numbers","description":"A man of Manasseh who died in the wilderness leaving only daughters. His case led to a landmark ruling granting inheritance rights to daughters when there are no sons.","volumes":["OT"]},
    {"name":"Korah","book":"Numbers","description":"A Levite who led a rebellion against Moses and Aaron, claiming all the congregation was holy. The earth opened and swallowed him and his followers as divine judgment.","volumes":["OT"]},
    {"name":"Eleazar","book":"Numbers","description":"Third son of Aaron who succeeded his father as high priest. Served alongside Moses in the second census and the division of the promised land.","volumes":["OT"]}
  ],
  "summaries": [
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":1,"summary":"God commands Moses to take a census of all men twenty years and older able to go to war, numbering 603,550 from twelve tribes; the Levites are exempted."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":2,"summary":"The twelve tribes are assigned specific positions around the tabernacle for encampment and marching order, with Judah leading in the east."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":3,"summary":"The Levites are numbered and assigned to the three clans of Gershon, Kohath, and Merari, each with specific tabernacle duties; they replace the firstborn."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":4,"summary":"A census of Levitical men aged 30-50 assigns the Kohathites, Gershonites, and Merarites their specific duties in transporting the tabernacle."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":5,"summary":"Laws are given for removing the unclean from camp, making restitution for wrongs, and the ritual for testing a wife suspected of unfaithfulness."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":6,"summary":"The Nazirite vow of consecration is detailed, and Moses is given the priestly blessing: 'The LORD bless thee, and keep thee.'"},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":7,"summary":"The twelve tribal leaders each bring identical offerings over twelve days for the dedication of the altar, totaling a vast amount of silver, gold, and animals."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":8,"summary":"Aaron lights the lampstand; the Levites are ceremonially purified through sprinkling, shaving, and sacrifice, then formally presented for tabernacle service."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":9,"summary":"Israel observes the Passover in the wilderness; provision is made for those unable to keep it on time; God's cloud guides the camp's movements."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":10,"summary":"Two silver trumpets are made for assembling the camp and sounding alarms; Israel departs Sinai in ordered march for the first time."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":11,"summary":"The people complain and crave meat; God sends quail but strikes the camp with a plague; Moses appoints seventy elders to share the burden of leadership."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":12,"summary":"Miriam and Aaron challenge Moses' authority; God affirms Moses as unique among prophets, and Miriam is struck with leprosy for seven days."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":13,"summary":"Twelve spies explore Canaan for forty days; they report a land of abundance but ten of them terrify the people with tales of giants."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":14,"summary":"Israel rebels and wants to return to Egypt; Moses intercedes; God pardons but decrees that the faithless generation will die in the wilderness over forty years."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":15,"summary":"Laws for grain and drink offerings in the promised land are given; a man is stoned for gathering sticks on the Sabbath; fringes are commanded."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":16,"summary":"Korah, Dathan, and Abiram lead a rebellion; the earth swallows the rebels, fire consumes 250 incense offerers, and a plague kills 14,700 more."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":17,"summary":"Twelve rods are placed before the LORD; Aaron's rod alone buds, blossoms, and produces almonds, confirming God's choice of the Levitical priesthood."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":18,"summary":"God defines the duties of priests and Levites at the tabernacle and establishes their support through tithes, offerings, and the firstborn redemption."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":19,"summary":"The ordinance of the red heifer is given for purification from contact with the dead, establishing water of separation for the camp's ritual cleanness."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":20,"summary":"Miriam dies at Kadesh; Moses strikes the rock instead of speaking to it, forfeiting his entry to the promised land; Aaron dies on Mount Hor."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":21,"summary":"Israel defeats Arad, is punished by fiery serpents for murmuring and healed by looking at a bronze serpent, then conquers Sihon and Og."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":22,"summary":"Balak king of Moab hires Balaam to curse Israel; God warns Balaam through visions and through his own donkey, who sees the angel and speaks."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":23,"summary":"Balaam delivers two oracles from Balak's altars, each time blessing Israel instead of cursing them, declaring God's irrevocable favor."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":24,"summary":"Balaam pronounces two more blessings on Israel, including the messianic prophecy of a Star and Sceptre rising from Jacob, then departs."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":25,"summary":"Israelite men sin with Moabite women at Baal-peor; a plague kills 24,000 until Phinehas' zealous act earns his family a covenant of perpetual priesthood."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":26,"summary":"A second census of the new generation counts 601,730 fighting men; the land is to be divided proportionally among the tribes."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":27,"summary":"The daughters of Zelophehad receive a ruling allowing daughters to inherit; God tells Moses to ascend Mount Abarim and commissions Joshua as his successor."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":28,"summary":"Detailed laws for the daily, Sabbath, new moon, and Passover offerings are restated as Israel prepares to enter the promised land."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":29,"summary":"Offerings for the Feast of Trumpets, Day of Atonement, and the eight days of the Feast of Tabernacles are prescribed."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":30,"summary":"Laws governing vows are given: a man's vow is binding; a woman's vow may be confirmed or annulled by her father or husband."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":31,"summary":"Israel wages war against Midian, slaying the five kings and Balaam; the spoil is purified and divided among the soldiers, congregation, and Levites."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":32,"summary":"The tribes of Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh request the lands east of Jordan and agree to fight alongside their brethren before settling."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":33,"summary":"A complete itinerary of Israel's forty-two camping stations from Egypt to the plains of Moab is recorded, with instructions to drive out Canaan's inhabitants."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":34,"summary":"God defines the precise boundaries of the promised land on all four sides and names the tribal leaders who will oversee the land's division."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":35,"summary":"Forty-eight Levitical cities are designated, including six cities of refuge; laws distinguishing murder from manslaughter are established."},
    {"book":"Numbers","chapter":36,"summary":"A supplemental ruling requires Zelophehad's daughters to marry within their tribe so that tribal inheritances remain intact across generations."}
  ],
